    "scope_boundary": "IN: Angular UI project (presentation layer), angular.json / build configuration, all .scss/.sass files, CI/CD steps that invoke the Angular build. OUT: Backend Java services, domain and data‑access layers, unrelated micro‑frontends, runtime business logic, and any non‑UI infrastructure.",
    "classification_assessment": "",
    "classification_confidence": -1,
    "affected_components": [
      "frontend‑app (presentation)",
      "frontend‑build‑pipeline (infrastructure)"
    ],
    "context_boundaries": [
      {
        "category": "technology_constraint",
        "boundary": "Angular 19 removes the legacy SASS compiler; the project must switch to the new @angular-devkit/build-angular:application builder to keep the build pipeline functional.",
        "severity": "blocking",
        "source_facts": [
          "ADR: UVZ-09-ADR-003 Frontend Build Strategy SASS Import Deprecation"
        ]
      },
      {
        "category": "dependency_risk",
        "boundary": "Existing SASS files may use deprecated import syntax (e.g., @import) that the new builder no longer supports, creating a risk of UI regressions after migration.",
        "severity": "caution",
        "source_facts": [
          "ADR: UVZ-09-ADR-003 Frontend Build Strategy SASS Import Deprecation"
        ]
      },
      {
        "category": "testing_constraint",
        "boundary": "Because the SASS compilation change can affect styling and component rendering, additional UI tests (unit, integration, visual regression) must be executed to verify no regressions are introduced.",
        "severity": "caution",
        "source_facts": [
          "Issue description: \"additional testing may be necessary to minimize the risk of potential regressions\""
        ]
      },
      {
        "category": "integration_boundary",
        "boundary": "The frontend build is triggered from the overall Gradle build (Gradle 8.2.1) and the CI pipeline; any change to the Angular build configuration must remain compatible with the existing Gradle scripts.",
        "severity": "info",
        "source_facts": [
          "tech_versions.json: Gradle 8.2.1",
          "tech_versions.json: Angular CLI 18‑lts"
        ]
      },
      {
        "category": "technology_constraint",
        "boundary": "The project currently uses Webpack 5.80.0 for bundling; the new Angular builder may replace or bypass Webpack for SASS processing, so compatibility with existing Webpack configuration must be verified.",
        "severity": "info",
        "source_facts": [
          "tech_versions.json: Webpack 5.80.0"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "architecture_notes": "WALKTHROUGH: The application consists of five containers; the UI lives in the **frontend‑app** container, which belongs to the **presentation** layer (≈287 components). The SASS compilation is part of the **frontend‑build‑pipeline** (infrastructure container) that is invoked by the Gradle build. Neighboring components include the Angular CLI configuration (angular.json), the Webpack config, and the CI/CD scripts that call `ng build`. Changing the SASS compiler will affect only the build pipeline and the SASS source files; runtime components (services, domain logic) remain untouched. Think of the map as: **Container: frontend‑app → Layer: presentation → Component: UI components (styles) ↔ Component: build pipeline (infrastructure)**. Your work will be on the build pipeline component and the style assets it processes.",
    "anticipated_questions": [
      {
        "question": "Do I need to modify the existing SASS files, or only the build configuration?",
        "answer": "Primarily the build configuration (angular.json) must be updated to use the new builder. However, you should audit the SASS files for deprecated @import statements because the new builder may reject them, and adjust them to the modern @use syntax where needed."
      },
      {
        "question": "Will the change affect the CI/CD pipeline or the Gradle build scripts?",
        "answer": "The CI/CD pipeline calls the Gradle build, which in turn triggers the Angular build. The new builder must be compatible with the existing Gradle scripts; typically no changes to Gradle are required, but you should verify that the `ng build` command still works from the Gradle task after the migration."
      },
      {
        "question": "What testing is expected after the migration?",
        "answer": "Run the full suite of UI unit tests (Karma), integration tests, and any visual regression tests (Playwright). Pay special attention to components that heavily rely on SASS variables or mixins, as styling changes are the most likely source of regressions."
      },
      {
        "question": "Is there any impact on other front‑end libraries (e.g., Angular Material, CDK)?",
        "answer": "Those libraries are already on the Angular 18 LTS versions and are compatible with the new builder. No library version changes are required, but ensure that their styles are still correctly imported after the migration."
      },
      {
        "question": "Do we need to upgrade Angular CLI to version 19 now?",
        "answer": "The migration is part of the broader Angular 19 upgrade. You can perform the SASS compiler switch while still on Angular 18, but the final verification should be done after the Angular CLI is upgraded to the 19 version to confirm end‑to‑end compatibility."
      }
    ],
    "linked_tasks": []
  }
